Accessibility

# 

<span key="5c76460e999d44e1bca71b2710db4575"><span offset-key="5c76460e999d44e1bca71b2710db4575:0">Accessibility</span></span>

<span key="e587a9a5174f4a6f9c0e0413f2c50c6b">**Accessibility**<span offset-key="e587a9a5174f4a6f9c0e0413f2c50c6b:1"> is a subset of inclusive design that focuses on accommodating people with disabilities or impairments.</span></span>

<span key="fa152ff4377e40a59edd494b8ae3c3f8"><span offset-key="fa152ff4377e40a59edd494b8ae3c3f8:0">In theory, accessibility should result from an effective inclusive design process. If we've designed a product accessibly, it means we've successfully anticipated a variety of differences in which people might interact with our product.</span></span>

<span key="90fb933714b5489fba3736df681851f8"><span offset-key="90fb933714b5489fba3736df681851f8:0">In practice, we need to develop a deep understanding of disability and design for accessibility accordingly.</span></span>

## 

<span key="651e307b93ce441db69a35f323c2ca92"><span offset-key="651e307b93ce441db69a35f323c2ca92:0">Understanding Disability</span></span>

<span key="1b7ba5e8a32d4023a5fb4137cc6b6a35"><span offset-key="1b7ba5e8a32d4023a5fb4137cc6b6a35:0">The first thing to recognize about disability is that it </span>**depends on context**<span offset-key="1b7ba5e8a32d4023a5fb4137cc6b6a35:2">. A person might be disabled in one context, but not in another. For example, a person with myopia (nearsightedness) might have no issue reading a newspaper, but might have an issue reading a billboard.</span></span>

<span key="34797b906e694c588f2d87750173f8c7"><span offset-key="34797b906e694c588f2d87750173f8c7:0">Another critical thing to understand about disability is that </span>**it isn't all-or-nothing**<span offset-key="34797b906e694c588f2d87750173f8c7:2">. There's a range for many impairments, where based on the design of your product, some people might need to invest slightly more effort to use a certain feature, some might need to invest a high amount of additional effort, and some might be excluded.</span></span>

<span key="83f9fe0203604295aa7fab4993464ca1"><span offset-key="83f9fe0203604295aa7fab4993464ca1:0">According to the </span></span><a href="https://www.worldbank.org/en/topic/disability#:~:text=Results-,One%20billion%20people%2C%20or%2015%25%20of%20the%20world%27s%20population%2C,million%20people%2C%20experience%20significant%20disabilities." class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="e91fb285c5a841c7ab45402836e06e82" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-9870_259-9871-237__"><span data-key="ef374c59160a40359507c83330b8bc81"><span data-offset-key="ef374c59160a40359507c83330b8bc81:0">World Bank (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="72d787d165984269856968f053737cdf"><span offset-key="72d787d165984269856968f053737cdf:0">, one billion people (15% of the world population) experience a form of disability. Designing for accessibility is a critical focus of UX design.</span></span>

## 

<span key="49274a133c2b4857a40db2d0b790af11"><span offset-key="49274a133c2b4857a40db2d0b790af11:0">Designing for Accessibility</span></span>

<span key="7eae56135cce47de8fbdfa185d6ed0b0"><span offset-key="7eae56135cce47de8fbdfa185d6ed0b0:0">There are two ways users might access our product: </span>**direct access**<span offset-key="7eae56135cce47de8fbdfa185d6ed0b0:2"> (using only features native to the app) and </span>**indirect access**<span offset-key="7eae56135cce47de8fbdfa185d6ed0b0:4"> (using an assistive technology like a screen reader).</span></span>

<span key="73e4953d8bf44307b761167d1774c4fb"><span offset-key="73e4953d8bf44307b761167d1774c4fb:0">Recognizing this will help accommodate both groups, and in some cases, inform whether you should develop a native feature to handle certain cases.</span></span>

<span key="420456a6e153415f8270b3ade0d34b4d"><span offset-key="420456a6e153415f8270b3ade0d34b4d:0">Here are just a few things to consider:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="c477b2177e5c437e8d9065cce269d29a">**Don't rely on color:**<span offset-key="c477b2177e5c437e8d9065cce269d29a:1"> Many users are colorblind or otherwise visually impaired. In addition, cultural differences can influence how colors are perceived. Make sure wherever you're using color to convey information, there's also an additional way that includes these users.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="f94f922a710742bdbbe38be0673490a2">**Make sure clickable/touchable areas are large:**<span offset-key="f94f922a710742bdbbe38be0673490a2:1"> Make it easy for users to interact with elements in your product. This helps a great diversity of users.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="92a2c46596964dd28a0eebd6e9ca68d4">**Ensure sufficient contrast among important elements:**<span offset-key="92a2c46596964dd28a0eebd6e9ca68d4:1"> Make sure it's easy to distinguish important elements from each other with contrast by default. For example, the W3C's </span></span><a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/UNDERSTANDING-WCAG20/visual-audio-contrast-contrast.html" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="df6a41f19a2c44bba0811ac469437fa6" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-9870_259-9871-237__"><span data-key="0c87309a600e4986bb1e837d24693549"><span data-offset-key="0c87309a600e4986bb1e837d24693549:0">Web Contrast Accessibility Guidelines 2.0 (Links to an external site.)</span></span></span></a><span key="d955031e3a5a4f919cfc65a8045ab4dd"><span offset-key="d955031e3a5a4f919cfc65a8045ab4dd:0"> define a minimum contrast ratio of 4.5:1 for most text.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="6198a8608997446aae6de7e0276c9d18">**Make sure all non-text content is also available in text.**<span offset-key="6198a8608997446aae6de7e0276c9d18:1"> For example, be sure to include any relevant text information during the design stage that should supplement non-text content, such as alt-text.</span></span>

<span key="6de0ea8d78e043b3bc08bd7b5030dcf0"><span offset-key="6de0ea8d78e043b3bc08bd7b5030dcf0:0">Another thing to consider is that some user differences are short-term, while others are long-term. A temporary medical condition might cause temporary disabilityâ€”and many circumstances that influence usability are unrelated to disability, like glare on a screen.</span></span>

<span key="32e9dc6ee88643b988824bcabd82cd2d"><span offset-key="32e9dc6ee88643b988824bcabd82cd2d:0">Consider all of these factors during the design process, and you'll go a long way toward building inclusively and accessibly.</span></span>
